id="loop-meta"><h1 class="loop-meta-title">Tag Archives: <span>Bike</span></h1><div
class="loop-meta-description"></div></div><div
id="post-4045" class="post-4045 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-transportation tag-bike tag-bixi tag-commuting tag-condo tag-infrastructure tag-kristyn-wong-tam tag-sharing tag-toronto"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2013/09/17/toronto-condo-developers-want-more-bike-sharing-less-focus-on-cars/" title="Permalink to Toronto Condo Developers Want More Bike Sharing, Less Focus on Cars" rel="bookmark">Toronto Condo Developers Want More Bike Sharing, Less Focus on Cars</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2013/09/17 9:07 am"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2013/09/17/toronto-condo-developers-want-more-bike-sharing-less-focus-on-cars/" title="Toronto Condo Developers Want More Bike Sharing, Less Focus on Cars" rel="bookmark">2013/09/17 9:07 am</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>Despite repeated efforts by Toronto&#8217;s mayor to make transportation in the city worse, things are improving. Local condo developers are finding ways to build condo towers that don&#8217;t require more parking than the building needs (an archaic law in the city wants room for two cars for every bedroom built). They are using the cash saved from not building room for cars to build infrastructure for bicycles &#8211; which the condo buyers are asking for.</p><p>Other cities around the world already do this and it&#8217;s thanks to the effort of the developers and councillor Kristyn Wong-Tam that Toronto benefits from this smart approach. With more people moving into the city bicycles make sense as a primary transportation source.</p><p><img
src="http://i2.wp.com/www.thingsaregood.com/wp-content/uploads/2007/11/wonderful-bike-icon.png?resize=300%2C300" alt="bike" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1310" data-recalc-dims="1" /></p><blockquote><p>The developers — major players Canderel, DiamondCorp and Lanterra — agreed to contribute to Bixi in exchange for permission to create fewer parking spaces than city rules require.</p><p>The city sometimes releases developers from parking requirements without demanding anything in return. Wong-Tam said she decided that she would attempt this time to insist on the Bixi contribution. The developers, she said, put up “no resistance whatsoever,” since they will spend far less than they would have had to spend to build parking they can’t sell.</p><p>Lanterra chief executive Barry Fenton said he never thought of the agreement as a cost-saver: he believes his company would have persuaded Wong-Tam to relax the requirements even without the Bixi payment. Citing a “fantastic” bike journey he took in Stockholm, he said investing in urban cycling “just really, really, really makes a lot of sense.”</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2013/09/11/bixi_condo_developers_contribute_1_million_to_toronto_bikeshare_expansion.html">Read more at The Star.</a></p><p><em>Thanks to Dan!</em></p><div
class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-1111807-4045-53838c8531cb5' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/#blog_id=1111807&amp;post_id=4045&amp;origin=www.thingsaregood.com&amp;obj_id=1111807-4045-53838c8531cb5' data-name='like-post-frame-1111807-4045-53838c8531cb5'><h3 class='sd-title'>Like this:</h3><div
