id="post-3512" class="post-3512 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-transportation tag-bicycle tag-bike tag-bloomberg tag-lanes tag-nyc tag-rob-ford"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2012/11/13/nyc-mayor-bloomberg-loves-bike-lanes/" title="Permalink to NYC Mayor Bloomberg Loves Bike Lanes" rel="bookmark">NYC Mayor Bloomberg Loves Bike Lanes</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2012/11/13 5:02 pm"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2012/11/13/nyc-mayor-bloomberg-loves-bike-lanes/" title="NYC Mayor Bloomberg Loves Bike Lanes" rel="bookmark">2012/11/13 5:02 pm</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>As Toronto fights smart planning and <a
href="http://www.citytv.com/toronto/citynews/news/local/article/235719--cyclists-to-continue-jarvis-street-bike-lane-protest">removes sustainable transportation infrastructure</a> (indeed, paying hundreds of thousands of dollars to do so), New York City Mayor Bloomberg continues to espouse how great bike lanes are. In NYC they have added a lot of miles of bike lanes and found local business get more business, neighbourhoods become nicer, and more people can get around easier than they did before!</p><blockquote><p>With the release by NYC DOT this week of <a
href="http://bikeportland.org/2012/10/25/money-talks-the-economic-impact-of-livable-streets-79306">a report showing the economic impact of their street projects</a>, Bloomberg wove the economic case into his speech. &#8220;Talk to merchants everywhere we&#8217;ve put protected bicycle lanes [and pedestrian plazas]&#8230; They will tell you that business is dramatically better than it was before.&#8221;</p><p>Bloomberg called New York City&#8217;s legacy of mega-highway building by former DOT Commissioner Robert Moses a &#8220;mistake&#8221; because &#8220;we bulldozed neighborhoods.&#8221;</p><p>With the mistakes of the past fading from view, Bloomberg seems to understand the direct link between how streets are used and whether or not a city succeeds. &#8220;We&#8217;re using the streets in ways they had not been used in a long time,&#8221; he said, &#8220;Cyclists and pedestrians and bus riders are as important — if not, I would argue <em>more important</em> — than automobile riders.&#8221;</p><p>While he acknowledged that bike lanes &#8220;are always controversial&#8221; he defended them by noting that, &#8220;more and more people are using them.&#8221;</p><p>Looking ahead, Bloomberg said he has no plans of letting naysayers or controversies stop the progress. &#8220;Transportation&#8230; it&#8217;s not sexy and it certainly invites controversy,&#8221; he said, but added, &#8220;We&#8217;ve just got to keep developing, keep building, sensibly, with some plans and community involvement; but not stopping.&#8221;</p></blockquote><p>As you can probably guess from my recent series of pro-bike lane posts, I am rather embarrassed by Toronto Mayor Rob Ford and his archaic approach to transit. When he&#8217;s out of office we may get to see some good news coming from Toronto again.</p><p><a
href="http://bikeportland.org/2012/10/26/nyc-mayor-cyclists-more-important-than-automobile-riders-79343">Read more here.</a></p><div
class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-1111807-3512-53838c8545d63' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/#blog_id=1111807&amp;post_id=3512&amp;origin=www.thingsaregood.com&amp;obj_id=1111807-3512-53838c8545d63' data-name='like-post-frame-1111807-3512-53838c8545d63'><h3 class='sd-title'>Like this:</h3><div
