id="post-2939" class="post-2939 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-art category-fun category-good-fact category-transportation tag-bike tag-good tag-toronto"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2011/08/15/good-bikes-on-the-streets-of-toronto/" title="Permalink to Good Bikes on the Streets of Toronto" rel="bookmark">Good Bikes on the Streets of Toronto</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2011/08/15 11:19 am"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2011/08/15/good-bikes-on-the-streets-of-toronto/" title="Good Bikes on the Streets of Toronto" rel="bookmark">2011/08/15 11:19 am</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p><a
href="http://blogthegoodbike.tumblr.com/">The Good Bike</a> project is bringing colour to the streets of Toronto. Bright neon bicycles are celebrating aspects of Toronto, they really are eye-catching.</p><blockquote><p>Over the past few weeks, more than 30 brightly painted bicycles, a few featuring baskets of potted plants, have popped up all over the city—orange at Queen and Dovercourt, blue at Dundas and Sackville, and pastel pink at College and Robert, among many others. On their own, the bikes may seem like isolated or even arbitrary acts of street art, but in reality, they&#8217;re part of a citywide network of bikes, their colours and locations carefully and specifically chosen to commemorate a piece of history, an urban hot spot, or a personal memory.</p><p>As with any infestation, even the nice ones, it started small—Vanessa Nicholas and Caroline Macfarlane, two OCAD U Student Gallery employees, found a creative way to deal with their distaste for a rusty, derelict bike abandoned on the street outside their place of work by painting it bright orange and planting flowers in its basket. They were met with enthusiasm from passersby but also with a big, angry ticket from the City of Toronto calling for its removal. With support from fans and friends interested in protecting public works of art, accelerated by media reaction and councilors Gary Crawford (Ward 36, Scarborough Southwest) and Adam Vaughan (Ward 20, Trinity-Spadina) City Hall eventually changed its mind and even Rob Ford hopped on the idea to turn the now-famous Orange Bike into a citywide project, in partnership with Macfarlane and Nicholas, known as the Good Bike Project.</p></blockquote><p>Read the full article at <a
href="http://torontoist.com/2011/08/the_invasion_of_the_neon_bikes.php">Torontoist</a>.</p><div
